    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1939-05-21T06:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1939-05-21T06:00:00-05:00" n="856"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d856">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">660H.1115/11: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Yugoslavia</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Lane</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Belgrade</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1939-05-21T12:00:00+01:00"
                            >May 21, 1939—noon</date>.<lb/>[Received May 21—11:49 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>143. In recent conversation with the Minister of Finance<note n="11"
                        xml:id="d856fn11">Vojin Djuričić.</note> he has referred to Yugoslavia’s
                    urgent need of raw cotton and to our large surplus crop, a part of which may be
                    destroyed. He inquired whether it would be possible for the Yugoslav Government
                    to purchase enough for its needs here amounting to about 300,000,000 dinars and
                    to establish a credit in the United States to finance the purchase but admitted
                    that he had not yet given careful consideration to the details. He inquired
                    whether some Government agency such as the RFC<note n="12" xml:id="d856fn12"
                        >Reconstruction Finance Corporation.</note> would be in a position to extend
                    such a credit. In reply I reminded him of the Johnson Act<note n="13"
                        xml:id="d856fn13">Approved April 13, 1934; 48 Stat. 574.</note> but agreed
                    to transmit his inquiry to the Department for decision.</p>
                <p>I referred to our having had until now between 60 and 70 per cent of Yugoslav
                    total cotton importations, to our not having been accorded a quota for any
                    articles on the control list with the exception of automobiles and trucks, and
                    to our desire to be assured of our share, based on our cotton importations
                    during a representative period. He replied that if the financing of the cotton
                    purchases in the United States could be arranged we should automatically have
                    permission to import according to Yugoslav needs.</p>
                <p>I should appreciate the Department’s telegraphic comment.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Lane</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
